 |filename2    = Rihanna - If It's Lovin' That You Want.ogg
 |title2       = "If It's Lovin' that You Want"
 |description2 = A 20 second sample of "If It's Lovin' that You Want", of which critics both praised Rihanna's vocal range<ref name="TheHindu">{{cite news|last=Vishnu|first=A|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2006/01/12/stories/2006011201300200.htm|title=Of sun, sea 'n' sand|work=[[The Hindu]]|publisher=[[The Hindu Group]]|accessdate=2011-10-02}}</ref> but also criticized her for sounding "too light" and "thin".<ref name="About.com">{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/rihannalovin.htm|title=Rihanna &ndash; If It's Lovin' That You Want (Def Jam)|publisher=[[About.com]], [[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> 
}}
After Rihanna signed a record deal with Def Jam Recordings, she began working with various producers for the debut album and continued to work with Rogers and Sturken, who had previously written and produced "Pon de Replay" and "The Last Time" for Rihanna's demo tape. Although Rihanna stated that when she first heard "Pon de Replay", she did not want to record it, expressing that she felt the song was "sing-songy", but grew to like the song at the end of the recording process.<ref name="ArtistDirect">{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/news/article/0,,3655378,00.html|title=Artist Directs Exclusive Interview With Rihanna!|publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|date=2006-05-12|accessdate=2011-12-13}}</ref> In an interview with Kidzworld, Rihanna explained how the pair helped her develop her song-writing abilities, saying Rogers and Sturken, who had worked with recording artists including [[Britney Spears]], [[Christina Aguilera]] and [[Kelly Clarkson]], helped her improve upon her song-writing abilities.<ref name="Kidzworld"/>

''Music of the Sun'' was inspired by [[caribbean music]], including [[Soca music|soca]], [[dancehall]], and [[reggae]], as well as corporating  [[dance-pop]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]].<ref name="Allmusic1">{{cite web|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/music-of-the-sun-r783863/credits|title=Music of the Sun &ndash; Rihanna|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2011-09-24}}</ref> The lead single "Pon de Replay" was written by Rogers, Sturken and Vada Nobles, and was produced by the first two. Musically, "Pon de Replay" draws influence from the musical genres of dance-pop, R&B and dancehall.<ref name="Allmusic1"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Walters|first=Barry|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/music-of-the-sun-20050908|title=Rihanna &ndash; Music of the Sun &ndash; Def Jam|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=2005-09-05|accessdate=2011-09-25}}</ref> Lyrically, the song is about asking the [[Disc jockey|DJ]] to play the protagonist's favorite song, as well as the fulfillment of dancing in a club.<ref name="MetroWeekly1">{{cite web|last=Rule|first=Doug|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/nightlife/soundwaves/?ak=2099|title=Soundwaves: Rihanna, Cascada, Duran Duran, more|work=[[Metro Weekly]]|publisher=Sean Bugg, Randy Shulman|date=2006-05-04|accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> "The Last Time", written and produced by Rogers and Sturken is an acoustic guitar driven ballad,<ref name="Kidzworld"/> while "Now That I Know" is a stripped down string driven song.<ref name="Kidzworld"/> In addition to working with Rogers and Sturken for the majority of the album, Rihanna worked with production teams [[Trackmasters|Poke & Tone of Trackmasters]] and [[Stargate (production team)|Stargate]].<ref name="Kidzworld"/> The former wrote and produced the second single released from the album, "[[If It's Lovin' that You Want]]", which Rihanna described as a "fun song".<ref name="Kidzworld"/> An [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song,<ref name="AllMusicPt2">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/if-its-lovin-that-you-want-pt-2-r1003110|title=If It's Lovin' That You Want Pt. 2|publisher=Allmusic, Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> "If It's Lovin' that You Want" is a song about a girl telling a boy that he should make her his girl, because she has what the boy wants.<ref name="MTVNews1">{{cite news|author=Brandee J. Tecson and Yasmine Richard|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1508016/20050819/rihanna.jhtml|title=Rihanna Insists She's Got What You Need In 'Pon De Replay' Follow-Up|publisher=[[MTV]], [[Viacom]]|date=2005-08-19|accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> A remix of the song entitled "If It's Lovin' That You Want &ndash; Part 2", which features [[Rapping|rap]] vocals by [[Cory Gunz]], was included as a bonus track on Rihanna's [[Album|sophomore album]], ''[[A Girl Like Me (Rihanna album)|A Girl Like Me]]'' (2006).<ref name="AllMusicPt2"/> Alongside Rogers and Sturken, Stargate co-wrote and co-produced "Let Me", which appears as the ninth song on the album.<ref name="Kidzworld"/> ''Music of the Sun'' contains a cover of [[Jamaica|Jamaican]] singer [[Dawn Penn]]{{'s}} "[[You Don't Love Me (No, No, No)]]", and features dancehall recording artist [[Vybz Kartel]].<ref name="Kidzworld"/>

==Response==
