Jason Birchmeier of [[Allmusic]] praised ''Music of the Sun'' and awarded it 3.5 stars out of 5; Birchmeier commented that the album presents Rihanna as "winsome rather than [a] wannabe," as well as how she managed to set herself apart from other dance-pop artists such as [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]] and [[Ciara]].<ref name="Allmusic1"/> Birchmeier further stated that "''Music of the Sun'' descends into faceless slow jams after a while, overall consistency not being among its attributes, but thankfully it picks up the pace toward the end&nbsp;... the result is one of the more engaging urban dance-pop albums of the year."<ref name="Allmusic1"/> Chantal Jenoure of ''[[The Jamaica Observer]]'' gave the album 3.5 stars out of 5, and praised the dancehall and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] composition on several of the songs, including "Pon de Replay", "Rush", "Let Me", "Music of the Sun" and "That La La La", writing that they make the listener feel "happy" and "carefree".<ref name="Jenoure"/>

Kelefa Sanneh of ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave ''Music of the Sun'' a "mixed" rating; Sanneh praised Rihanna for combining dancehall and reggae genres with that of more popular and mainstream ones, noting that the combination between dancehall and [[Pop music|pop]] resulted in "[Pon de Replay being] one [of] the summer's biggest and most seductive club tracks."<ref name="Sanneh"/> However, Sanneh noted that Rihanna sounds "stranded" when there is not a beat to sing along to.<ref name="Sanneh"/> Liam Colle praised the album and its Caribbean infused beats and gave ''Music of the Sun'' a rating of 5 out of 10.<ref name="Colle"/> Barry Walters of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' rated it 2.5 out of 5 stars and described the album as lacking the replay value, ingenuity and rhythm of the single with "generic [[vocal hiccups]] and frills" of US R&B inflecting upon her "Caribbean charm".<ref name="Walters"/> Sal Cinquemani of [[Slant Magazine]] awarded the album 2.5 stars out of 5, describing the album as a "glut of teen R&B chanteuses" and described the lead single "Pon de Replay" as "a dancehall-pop mixture that owes plenty of its sweat and shimmy to Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles' "[[Baby Boy (Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles song)|Baby Boy]]".<ref name="Cinquemani"/> Evan Serpick of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' was critical of ''Music of the Sun'' and rated it as a C grade album, writing "The 17-year-old's vibrant vocals lift tracks like 'That La La La' and 'Let Me,' but this bland dancehall/R&B debut is filled with chintzy production and maudlin arrangements that block out the Music of the Sun."<ref name="Serpick"/>

===Commercial performance===
In the United States, ''Music of the Sun'' debuted and peaked at number 10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart in the chart issue dated September 17, 2005.<ref name="US200Debut">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/west-registers-no-1-album-debut-1001055714.story#/news/west-registers-no-1-album-debut-1001055714.story|title=West 'Registers' No. 1 Album Debut|date=2005-08-24|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|date=2005-09-17|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref><ref name="ChartHistory">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/west-registers-no-1-album-debut-1001055714.story#/charts/billboard-200?chartDate=2005-09-17|title=Week of September 17, 2005|work=Billboard|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=2005-09-17|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> The album spent a total of 35 weeks on the chart.<ref name="ChartHistory"/> ''Music of the Sun'' debuted on the U.S. [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart at number six in the same chart issue, and spent a total of 44 weeks on the chart.<ref name="ChartHistory"/> After five months of release, the album was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on January 1, 2006, denoting shipments of over 500,000 copies.<ref name="RIAA">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=rihanna&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=Artist&perPage=25|title=Searchable Database|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|date=2006-01-01|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> As of July 23, 2010, the album had sold 593,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/column/chartbeat/ask-billboard-rating-rihanna-1004105967.story?tag=hpfeed`|title=Ask Billboard: Rating Rihanna|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=2010-07-23|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> In Canada, ''Music of the Sun'' debuted and peaked at number seven on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]] in the chart issue September 17, 2005, but dropped out of the top ten the following week.<ref name="CanadaDebut">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/rihanna/chart-history/658897#/charts/canadian-albums?chartDate=2005-09-17|title=Week of September 17, 2005|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielson Company|date=2005-09-17|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> After four months of release, the album was certified platinum by [[Music Canada]] for shipments of over 100,000 copies.<ref name="CanadaCert">{{cite web|url=http://www.cria.ca/gold/1205_g.php|title=Gold & Platinum: December 2005|publisher=[[Music Canada]]|date=2005-12-01|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> 

Outside of the United States and Canada, ''Music of the Sun'' failed to achieve a comparable level of chart success. In the United Kingdom, the album debuted and peaked at number 35 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] in the chart issue October 10, 2005.<ref name="UKDebut">{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/2005-09-10/|title=2005 Top 40 Official UK Albums Archive &ndash; 10th September 2005|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|date=2005-09-10|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> In its second week charting, ''Music of the Sun'' fell by three positions to number 38, and dropped out of the Official UK Top 40 the following week.<ref name="UKSecondWeek">{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/2005-09-17/|title=2005 Top 40 Official UK Albums Archive &ndash; 17th September 2005|publisher=The Official Charts Company|date=2005-09-17|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> On May 12, 2006, the album was certified gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) denoting shipments of over 100,000 copies.<ref name="BPI">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|title=BPI <U+2013> Certified Awards Search|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|date=2006-05-12|accessdate=2011-12-14|format=To access, enter the search parameter "Rihanna" and select "Search by Artist"}}</ref> Elsewhere in Europe, the album debuted on the [[Swiss Music Charts|Swiss Albums Chart]] at number 46 in the chart issue September 11, 2005, and peaked at number 38 four weeks later.<ref name="SwissAlbum">{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=Rihanna&titel=Music+Of+The+Sun&cat=a|title=Rihanna &ndash; Music of the Sun (Album)|work=''hitparade.ch''|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2011-12-14|language=German}}</ref> In Austria, ''Music of the Sun'' debuted on the [[<U+00D6>3 Austria Top 40|Austrian Albums Chart]] at number 61 in the chart issue September 18, 2005, and peaked at number 45 the following week.<ref name="AustrianAlbum">{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Rihanna&titel=Music+Of+The+Sun&cat=a|title=Rihanna &ndash; Music of the Sun (Album)|work=''austriancharts.at''|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2011-12-14|language=Austrian-German}}</ref> The album debuted and peaked at number 93 on the [[Syndicat National de l'<U+00C9>dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]] in the chart issue September 24, 2005.<ref name="FrenchAlbum">{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Rihanna&titel=Music+Of+The+Sun&cat=a|title=Rihanna &ndash; Music of the Sun (Album)|work=''lescharts.com''|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2011-12-14|language=French}}</ref> In The Netherlands, ''Music of the Sun'' debuted and peaked at number 98 on the [[Dutch Albums Chart#Mega Album Top 100|Dutch Albums Chart]] in the chart issue April 29, 2006, and spent one week on the chart.<ref name="DutchAlbum">{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Rihanna&titel=Music+Of+The+Sun&cat=a|title=Rihanna &ndash; Music of the Sun (Album)|work=''dutchcharts.nl''|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2011-12-14|language=Dutch}}</ref> In New Zealand, the album debuted on the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand Albums Chart]] at number 40 in the chart issue September 26, 2005.<ref name="NLAlbum">{{cite web|url=http://charts.org.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Rihanna&titel=Music+Of+The+Sun&cat=a|title=Rihanna &ndash; Music of the Sun (Album)|work=''charts.org.nz''|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> Between September 29 and October 10, 2005, ''Music of the Sun'' dropped out of the top-40 albums chart, but made a re-entry at number 40 on October 10, 2005.<ref name="NLAlbum"/> In its fourth week charting, the album peaked at number 26.<ref name="NLAlbum"/>

==Singles==
"Pon de Replay" was released as the album's lead single on May 24, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Pon-Replay-Vinyl-Rihanna/dp/B0009JPVDS/ref=sr_1_45?ie=UTF8&qid=1318062800&sr=8-45|title=Rihanna &ndash; Pon de Replay|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=2011-12-04}}</ref> It received positive reviews from music critics, who praised the West Indian and Caribbean inspired composition.<ref name="Lamb1">{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/reviews/gr/rihannapon.htm|title=Review Of Rihanna's 'Pon De Replay'|publisher=[[About.com]]. [[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=2011-09-25}}</ref> However, Bill Lamb of [[About.com]] criticized the song, writing that the lyrics did not make the listener feel intellectually challenged or provoke thought as to what the song meant.<ref name="Lamb1"/> The song peaked at number one on the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand Singles Chart]]<ref name="PondeReplayNewZealand"/> and number two on the U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] chart and [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name="PondeReplayUS"/><ref name="PonDeReplayUK"/> An accompanying music video was directed by [[Little X]] and features Rihanna in a club environment.<ref name="KidzWorld2">{{cite web|url=http://www.kidzworld.com/article/5855-rihanna-interview-pg-2|title=Rihanna Interview (pg. 2)|publisher=Kidzworld|accessdate=201109-25}}</ref> "If It's Lovin' that You Want" was released as the second and final single from ''Music of the Sun'' on December 2, 2005.<ref name="NorwayiTunes">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/no/album/if-its-lovin-that-you-want/id101833312|title=If It's Lovin' That You Want &ndash; Single|publisher=iTunes Store (NO)|date=2005-12-02|accessdate=2011-10-01|language=Norwegian}}</ref> The song received mixed reviews from critics, with the majority praising and criticizing Rihanna's vocal performance.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/rihannalovin.htm|title=Rihanna &ndash; If It's Lovin' That You Want (Def Jam)|publisher=About.com, The New York Times Company|accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> The song failed to replicate the chart success which "Pon de Replay" experienced, peaking at number 36 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart<ref name="IfItsLovinUS"/> and inside the top forty of multiple other charts. An accompanying music video was directed by [[Marcus Raboy]] and features Rihanna in a beach setting.<ref name="MTVNews1">{{cite news|author=Brandee J. Tecson and Yasmine Richard|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1508016/20050819/rihanna.jhtml|title=Rihanna Insists She's Got What You Need In 'Pon De Replay' Follow-Up|publisher=[[MTV]], [[Viacom]]|date=2005-08-19|accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref>

